\right).

(b) Using your parametrization in part (a), set up an 
integral for calculating the circulation of \vec{F} 
around C.

Note that this isn't a very pleasant integral to evaluate by hand (though we could easily find a numerical estimate for it). It's easier to find \int_C
abla f\cdot d\vec r as the sum \int_{C_1}
abla f\cdot d\vec r + \int_{C_2}
abla f\cdot d\vec r, where C_1 is the line segment from (0,0) to (1,0) and C_2 is the line segment from (1,0) to (1,\pi/2). Calculate these integrals to find the change in f.

So that the change in f = \int_C
abla f\cdot\vec r = \int_{C_1}
abla f\cdot d\vec r + \int_{C_2}
abla f\cdot d\vec r =

static.solution:
(a) The parameterization is \vec r(t) = (x(t),y(t)) = \langle t, \pi\,t/2angle. Then \vec r\,'(t) = \langle 1, \pi/2angle, so that \int_C
abla f\cdot d\vec r = \int_0^1 \langle -4xe^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(5yight), 10e^{-x^{2}}\cos\!\left(5yight)angle\cdot \langle 1,\pi/2angle\,dt = \int_0^1 \left(5\cdot 2 rac{\pi }{2}e^{-t^{2}}\cos\!\left( rac{5\pi t}{2}ight)-4te^{-t^{2}}\sin\!\left( rac{5\pi t}{2}ight)ight)\,dt. As noted, it's simpler to integrate on the pair of line segments C_1 from (0,0) to (1,0) and C_2 from (1,0) to (1,\pi/2). Parameterizing these in a manner similar to our parameterization of C, on C_1 we have \vec r = \langle t, 0angle and on C_2 \vec r = \langle 1, \pi t/2angle. Then \int_{C_1}
abla f\cdot d\vec r = \int_0^1 0\,dt = 0, and \int_{C_2}
abla f\cdot d\vec r = \int_0^1  rac{\pi}{2}\,10\,e^{-1}\,\cos(5 rac{\pi}{2}\,t)\,dt = 2 e^{-1}, so that the change in f is (2 e^{-1}) + (0) = 2 e^{-1}.
(b) The other way to find the change in f between these two points is to first find f. To do this, observe that -4xe^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(5yight)\,\vec i + 10e^{-x^{2}}\cos\!\left(5yight)\,\vec j =  rac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(2e^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(5yight) ight) \vec i +  rac{\partial}{\partial y}\left(2e^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(5yight) ight) \vec j = 
abla \left(2e^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(5yight)ight). So one possibility for f is f(x,y)=e^{x^2}\sin y. Thus, \mbox{Change in } f igg|_{(0,0)}^{(1,\pi/2)} = 2e^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(5yight)  igg|_{(0,0)}^{(1,\pi/2)}= 2 e^{-1} - 0 = 2 e^{-1}.

