statement.p:
Use the divergence theorem to calculate the flux of 
the vector field \vec{F}(x,y,z) = x^3 \vec{i}
+ y^3 \vec{j} + z^3 \vec{k}
out of the closed, outward-oriented surface S 
bounding the solid x^2 + y^2 \leq 4, \ 
0 \leq z \leq 5.

static.solution:
\mbox{div}\,{\vec{F}} = 4\cdot 2x + 3\cdot 2y + 4\cdot 2z. So, if W is the interior of the box, we have \int_{S}\vec{F} \cdot d\vec{A} = \int_{W}(4\cdot 2x + 3\cdot 2y + 4\cdot 2z)dV = \int_{1}^{4}\int_{0}^{3}\int_{0}^{1}(4\cdot 2x + 3\cdot 2y + 4\cdot 2z)dz\,dy\,dx. Integrating through each of the integrals in turn, we have \int_{S}\vec{F} \cdot d\vec{A} = \int_{1}^{4}\int_{0}^{3} 4\cdot 2x\,z + 3\cdot 2y\,z + 4z^{2}\bigg|_{z=0}^{z=1}\, dy\,dx = \int_{1}^{4}\int_{0}^{3} 8 x + 6 y + 4\,dy\,dx = \int_{1}^{4} 8 x y + 3 y^2 + 4 y\bigg|_{y=0}^{y=3}\,dx = \int_{1}^{4} 24 x + 27 + 12\, dx = 12 x^2 + 27 x + 12 x\bigg|_{x=1}^{x=4} = 297.
Finding flux directly, note that on the faces x=4 and x=1 the normal vectors to the surfaces are \vec i and -\vec i respectively, so that \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \pm 4x^{2}\,dy\,dz (where x is evaluated at 4 or 1), and similarly on y = 3 and y = 0, and z = 1 and z = 0, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \pm 3y^{2}\,dx\,dz and \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \pm 4z^{2}\,dx\,dy, respectively. Thus on y = 0 and z = 0 the flux is zero. On the remaining faces, we have
(1) On x = 4, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{0}^{3}\int_{0}^{1}\,64\,dz\,dy = 192;
(2) On x = 1, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{0}^{3}\int_{0}^{1}\,4\,dz\,dy = -12;
(3) On y = 3, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{1}^{4}\int_{0}^{1}\,27\,dz\,dx = 81; and
(4) On z = 1, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{1}^{4}\int_{0}^{3}\,4\,dy\,dx = 36. Thus the total flux is the sum of these, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = 297.
